========================================
AGENT_GUIDE.txt
AI DEVELOPMENT INSTRUCTIONS
========================================


PURPOSE
----------------------------------------
This document defines how AI coding assistants should work on this project.

The goal is to ensure AI tools generate correct code without introducing unnecessary complexity.


PROJECT SUMMARY
----------------------------------------
This is an internal web platform used by a school coding club to run Python competitions.

Students solve coding problems and submit Python solutions.

Admins manually review submissions and award XP.

The platform runs entirely on Cloudflare infrastructure.

Scale is small (~30 students).


TECH STACK (STRICT)
----------------------------------------
Frontend
React with Vite (or Next.js)

Hosting
Cloudflare Pages

Backend
Cloudflare Workers (TypeScript)

Database
Cloudflare D1 (SQLite)

Global State
Cloudflare KV

Authentication
Clerk

Python Runtime
Pyodide running in the browser


AI agents must NOT introduce alternative technologies.


ABSOLUTE RULES
----------------------------------------

1. DO NOT introduce new frameworks or infrastructure.

2. DO NOT replace Cloudflare Workers with Express, FastAPI, or any server.

3. DO NOT use Docker, containers, or Kubernetes.

4. DO NOT run Python on the backend.

5. DO NOT introduce websockets unless explicitly requested.

6. DO NOT add unnecessary dependencies.

7. DO NOT create microservices.

8. DO NOT implement complex anti-cheat systems.

9. DO NOT implement automated judging systems.

10. Python execution must always happen in the browser using Pyodide.


KEEP THE PROJECT SIMPLE.


PROJECT STRUCTURE
----------------------------------------

The repository should follow this structure.


root

frontend/
React application

worker/
Cloudflare Worker backend

database/
D1 migration files

docs/
project documentation

shared/
shared types and utilities


AI agents should respect this structure.


BACKEND RULES
----------------------------------------

Backend must run entirely inside a Cloudflare Worker.

Use TypeScript.

All API routes should live under:

/api/


Example routes

/api/leaderboard
/api/problems
/api/submissions
/api/admin/submissions
/api/admin/review
/api/admin/toggle


Workers must interact with:

D1 for persistent data
KV for app toggle state


Do NOT store structured data in KV.


AUTHENTICATION RULES
----------------------------------------

Authentication is handled by Clerk.

AI agents must assume the frontend already has a Clerk session.

Worker endpoints must verify the session.

Only allow users whose email ends with:

@psbbschools.edu.in

Reject all other domains.


ADMIN ACCESS
----------------------------------------

Admins are defined by a hardcoded list of email addresses.

Example logic:

If user email exists in ADMIN_EMAILS list
role = admin

Otherwise
role = member


DATABASE RULES
----------------------------------------

Database is Cloudflare D1.

Use SQLite syntax.

Tables required:

users
problems
submissions


Avoid complex joins and keep queries simple.

Use parameterized queries.


APP TOGGLE SYSTEM
----------------------------------------

The application has a global ON/OFF state.

This state is stored in Cloudflare KV.

Key:

app_status

Values:

ON
OFF


Worker must check this before processing requests.

If status = OFF

Members can only access:

/api/leaderboard

Admins bypass this restriction.


SUBMISSION FLOW
----------------------------------------

1. Student submits code.

2. Worker stores submission in D1.

3. Submission status = pending.

4. Admin reviews submission.

5. Admin approves or rejects.

6. If approved:
User XP increases.


SUBMISSION STATUS VALUES

pending
approved
rejected


FRONTEND RULES
----------------------------------------

Frontend must be a React application.

The UI should remain minimal.

Students only see two main pages:

Competition page
Python interpreter page


COMPETITION PAGE

Displays:

problem description
code editor
submit button
submission history


PYTHON INTERPRETER PAGE

Loads Pyodide.

Runs Python in browser.

No backend execution.


PYODIDE RULES
----------------------------------------

Pyodide is large (~6MB).

AI agents must lazy load Pyodide only when the interpreter page loads.

Do not load Pyodide globally.


ADMIN DASHBOARD
----------------------------------------

Admins should have access to:

submission review queue
user list
leaderboard
competition toggle


The dashboard should remain simple.


ERROR HANDLING
----------------------------------------

All API endpoints must return structured JSON responses.

Example success response

status: success
data: ...


Example error response

status: error
message: ...


Do not return raw stack traces.


CODE STYLE
----------------------------------------

Prefer clear readable code.

Avoid clever abstractions.

Prefer explicit logic over magic frameworks.

Keep files small and modular.


TESTING
----------------------------------------

Basic manual testing is sufficient.

No complex testing frameworks are required.


WHEN UNSURE
----------------------------------------

If the AI agent is unsure about a decision:

1. Prefer the simplest solution.
2. Avoid adding new technologies.
3. Follow existing architecture.


FINAL PRINCIPLE
----------------------------------------

This project prioritizes:

clarity
simplicity
maintainability

NOT complexity.


End of AI guide.